01:36.401 --> 01:41.746
So if you have teenagers, if you have young kids, the service is gonna be designed for them to be able to engage.

01:41.794 --> 01:43.917
And we would love for you to join us for that weekend.

01:43.957 --> 01:44.938
It's going to be really special.

01:44.978 --> 01:47.141
But for today, you're stuck with me.

01:47.922 --> 01:49.605
And because of that, we need some extra prayer.

01:49.805 --> 01:53.009
So we're going to go before the Lord and pray and ask Him to speak to us through His Word.

01:53.029 --> 01:53.670
Let's pray together.

01:56.895 --> 01:59.018
Heavenly Father, we thank You for Your goodness to us.

02:00.199 --> 02:01.902
That Your mercies are new every morning.

02:03.364 --> 02:07.449
And we needed Him this morning as much as we needed Him yesterday, and we'll need them again tomorrow.

02:08.471 --> 02:10.834
So we say thank You for the sacrifice of Jesus.

02:11.714 --> 02:13.816
that gives us grace and forgiveness today.

02:14.977 --> 02:23.867
We approach your throne with humility, but your word also tells us we can approach your throne with boldness, because we have a God who listens to us.

02:24.628 --> 02:26.450
Thank you that you hear the prayers of your people.

02:26.550 --> 02:36.040
So today we pray and ask for you to speak to us, like children that are gathered by the feet of their father, ready to listen to what their father has to say.

02:36.100 --> 02:36.821
That's us today.

02:38.202 --> 02:39.023
We wanna hear from you.

02:40.265 --> 02:41.586
If there's anyone here

02:42.114 --> 02:45.919
who needs to be built up and encouraged today, I pray that your word would do that.

02:46.941 --> 02:53.030
If there's anyone here who needs to be comforted today by the power of your word, I pray you would do that, Lord.

02:54.292 --> 03:09.874
And if there's anyone here who needs to be convicted, if there's correction in our hearts, even my own, Lord, if there's anything in my heart that needs to be corrected or shifted to fall in alignment with your word, I ask you to do that today in all of us.

03:10.754 --> 03:12.176
Speak to us by your grace.

03:12.256 --> 03:14.859
We pray in Jesus' name.

03:14.879 --> 03:15.079
Amen.

03:16.341 --> 03:18.003
I want to begin this morning with a question.

03:19.304 --> 03:21.467
What kind of legacy do you want to leave?

03:22.829 --> 03:26.052
I've been thinking about that question a lot in my own life over the last two weeks.

03:27.514 --> 03:29.817
How do I want my kids and my wife to remember me?

03:31.059 --> 03:33.562
How do I want those I served with to remember me?

03:34.523 --> 03:36.645
I think it's an important question that we all need to ask.

03:36.665 --> 03:37.266
You know why?

03:37.794 --> 03:41.278
Because every day, you're building that legacy, whether you realize it or not.

03:42.079 --> 03:51.831
The conversations you have, the decisions you make, every single choice is building the kind of lifestyle that will leave a legacy here on the surface.

03:51.851 --> 03:52.873
So how do you wanna be remembered?

03:54.074 --> 03:56.037
What kind of legacy do you wanna leave behind?

03:57.138 --> 04:00.803
The reason I start with that question is because of the chapter that we're gonna read.

04:00.883 --> 04:06.770
Here in second Samuel 20, David is probably starting to ask those same questions about legacy.

04:07.298 --> 04:12.468
Most scholars would believe at this point in time, David is around 70 years old.

04:13.309 --> 04:18.739
Today, we're going to see how he passes off his faith and his leadership to the next generation in Israel.

04:19.060 --> 04:22.827
Now, before we dive into the text, let's recap where we are in the story.

04:22.907 --> 04:24.530
David has been through a lot, hasn't he?

04:24.834 --> 04:26.156
He's been through civil war.

04:26.296 --> 04:28.640
His own son Absalom rebelled against him.

04:28.681 --> 04:30.163
They had this great battle.

04:30.383 --> 04:31.646
Absalom has been killed.

04:32.126 --> 04:36.053
David has mourned for his son, and now he's returning back home to Jerusalem.

04:36.113 --> 04:38.838
The true king is coming back, which is a great thing.

04:38.858 --> 04:40.200
You think all is well, right?

04:40.761 --> 04:41.362
However,

04:41.634 --> 04:47.623
There's a dispute happening in Israel between the tribe of Judah and the tribes of Israel, and that's summed up at the end of chapter 19.

04:47.683 --> 04:51.730
I want to read verse 43 to you because it kind of sets us up for what we're going to read today.

04:51.750 --> 05:00.864
2 Samuel 19, 43, it says, the men of Israel answered the men of Judah, we have 10 shares in the king, so we have a greater claim on David than you have.

05:01.285 --> 05:03.008
Why then do you treat us with contempt?

05:03.348 --> 05:05.792
Weren't we the first to speak of bringing back our king?

05:06.193 --> 05:07.154
What's happening here?

05:07.362 --> 05:12.588
The men of Judah and the men of Israel are fighting over who has a greater right to honor David.

05:12.608 --> 05:13.188
Isn't that silly?

05:13.609 --> 05:15.631
Like, we love David more than you.

05:15.751 --> 05:17.052
We wanted to bring him back first.

05:17.092 --> 05:18.394
No, we love him more than you.

05:18.414 --> 05:19.295
We want to do our honor.

05:19.315 --> 05:22.258
And they're fighting each other over who gets to honor the king more.

05:23.159 --> 05:26.562
But that tension that's building, it's only going to get worse.

05:27.403 --> 05:31.648
David already suffered through one civil war, and he's about to endure another one.

05:31.688 --> 05:33.650
Look at me, 2 Samuel 20, verse 1.

05:34.914 --> 05:41.263
Now a troublemaker named Shiba, the son of Bakiri, a Benjamin, happened to be there.

05:41.864 --> 05:47.432
He sounded the trumpet and shouted, we have no share in David, no part in Jesse's son.

05:47.932 --> 05:49.635
Every man to his tent, Israel.

05:50.116 --> 05:59.228
So all the men of Israel deserted David to follow Shiba, the son of Bakiri, but the men of Judah stayed by their king all the way from the Jordan to Jerusalem.

05:59.629 --> 06:00.230
Let's stop right there.

06:01.071 --> 06:03.154
Man, David can't catch a break, can he?

06:03.650 --> 06:08.916
One after the other, people are rebelling against him, starting an entire war against him.

06:08.936 --> 06:11.119
And this time, it's a man named Shiba.

06:11.499 --> 06:12.260
He's a Benjamin.

06:12.440 --> 06:17.586
And all he does is sound a trumpet and shout, and everyone deserts David to follow him.

06:17.626 --> 06:18.847
That must have been some trumpet.

06:18.947 --> 06:22.872
I don't know what that was, but he got everyone in Israel to desert David.

06:23.693 --> 06:31.762
And you would be wise to ask the question, how is it possible that the people of Israel desert the greatest king they've ever had?

06:32.162 --> 06:40.954
David is the greatest king in Israel's history, and all of these people are just like that, just some trumpet and some shouting, and all of a sudden they abandon him.

06:40.974 --> 06:41.976
How is that possible?

06:42.416 --> 06:43.918
Well, there's two factors at play here.

06:43.958 --> 06:49.786
Number one, this happens because it's a consequence of David's sin with Bathsheba.

06:50.387 --> 06:58.098
If you remember back in 2 Samuel, chapter 12, Nathan prophesied from the Lord all of the things that would happen to David because of his sin,

06:58.210 --> 06:59.993
One of them sounds like this in verse 10.

07:00.333 --> 07:07.764
Now therefore, the sword will never depart from your house because you despised me and took the wife of Uriah the Hittite to be your own.

07:08.445 --> 07:11.410
It sounds like the sword is not departing from David's house, is it?

07:11.871 --> 07:17.860
He's continuing to have this tension in these battles as a consequence of his sin, but there's another factor at play here.

07:19.001 --> 07:23.388
Verse one starts with calling Sheba, this traitor, a troublemaker.

07:23.548 --> 07:25.591
Don't you love how the Bible translates things?

07:25.671 --> 07:27.474
This troublemaker named Sheba.

07:27.746 --> 07:37.219
But that word that is translated to troublemaker in the Hebrew, it's most often translated to the word accuser, but it's also used all throughout the Old Testament to describe guess who?

07:37.920 --> 07:38.280
Satan.

07:39.983 --> 07:40.824
So what's happening here?

07:41.425 --> 07:43.487
This isn't just the consequence of David's sin.

07:43.948 --> 07:47.613
Satan is actively working to pull God's people away from the true king.

07:48.294 --> 07:51.158
And listen, church, the same thing is happening in our world today.

07:51.879 --> 07:57.106
Satan is actively working to pull God's people away from their true king.

07:57.314 --> 07:57.714
Guess what?

07:57.755 --> 08:00.738
Jesus is the greatest king that you could ever possibly have.

08:01.039 --> 08:02.701
He has been nothing but good to you.

08:02.741 --> 08:04.803
He has built you up.

08:04.823 --> 08:06.465
He's given you hope and a future.

08:06.846 --> 08:12.393
And yet you have a very real enemy that wants nothing more than to distract you away from Jesus.

08:12.513 --> 08:18.620
And I am surprised how easily God's people turn away from the true king to Satan's distractions.

08:19.081 --> 08:23.346
Someone blows a trumpet and starts shouting and we're like, ooh, look at this.

08:23.522 --> 08:28.227
And we just walk away from Jesus so easily, just like the men of Israel did with David.

08:28.247 --> 08:30.210
Listen, don't fall for the enemy's trap.

08:30.750 --> 08:31.992
Don't fall for the schemes.

08:32.112 --> 08:34.595
Don't abandon your king so easily.

08:34.635 --> 08:35.796
He loves you.

08:36.277 --> 08:40.602
He's the greatest path that you could ever walk down is walking in obedience to Jesus.

08:40.962 --> 08:42.424
Don't be so easily tricked.

08:42.844 --> 08:45.727
Don't be so easily fooled.

08:45.747 --> 08:47.169
I love how this ends in verse two.

08:47.189 --> 08:51.474
It says, the men of Judah stayed by their king all the way from Jordan to Jerusalem.

08:51.874 --> 08:56.158
Christians in their own listen, be like the men of Judah, be the ones who stick by your king.

08:56.218 --> 09:10.572
And I'll even say this, even if nobody else does, even if you're the only one in your school, the only one in your office, the only one in your family group chat that's walking in obedience to Christ, stay loyal to him, because if you do, you won't regret it.

09:10.733 --> 09:11.834
Let's keep reading in verse three.

09:12.414 --> 09:15.457
We're gonna read through verse 13, parents, this is the graphic part.

09:16.038 --> 09:16.578
That's what it says.

09:17.639 --> 09:20.242
When David returned to his palace in Jerusalem,

09:20.578 --> 09:25.745
He took the 10 concubines that he had left to take care of the palace, and he put them in a house under guard.

09:26.306 --> 09:29.009
He provided for them, but had no sexual relations with them.

09:29.390 --> 09:32.734
And they were kept in confinement to the day of their death, living as widows.

09:33.255 --> 09:39.323
Then the king said to Amasa, some and the men of Judah to come to me within three days and be here yourself.

09:39.744 --> 09:44.991
But when Amasa went to summon Judah, he took longer than the time the king had set for him, verse six.

09:45.492 --> 09:50.258
David said to Abishai, now Shiba, son of the Kiri will do us more harm than Absalom did.

09:50.562 --> 09:55.887
Take your master's men and pursue him, or he will find fortified cities and escape from us.

09:56.328 --> 10:02.274
So Joab's men and the Carathites and the Pelithites and all the mighty warriors went out under the command of Abishai.

10:03.095 --> 10:06.258
They marched out from Jerusalem to pursue Shiba, son of Bakiri.

10:06.638 --> 10:11.123
Verse eight, while they were at the Great Rock in Gibeon, Amasa came to meet them.

10:11.483 --> 10:17.970
And Joab was wearing his military tunic and strapped over it at his waist was a belt with a dagger in its sheath.

10:18.274 --> 10:23.582
As he stepped forward, it dropped out of its sheath, and Joab said to Amasa, how are you, my brother?

10:23.602 --> 10:27.247
Then Joab took Amasa by the beard with his right hand to kiss him.

10:27.788 --> 10:35.680
Amasa was not on his guard against the dagger in Joab's hand, and Joab plunged it into his belly, and his intestines spilled out on the ground.

10:36.181 --> 10:38.204
Without being stabbed again, Amasa died.

10:38.665 --> 10:47.698
Then Joab and his brother Abishai pursued Shiba, son of Bakiri, and one of Joab's men stood beside Amasa and said, whoever favors Joab and whoever is for David,

10:47.778 --> 10:49.180
Let him follow Joab.

10:49.200 --> 10:52.724
Verse 12, Amasa lay wallowing in his blood in the middle of the road.

10:53.184 --> 10:56.368
And the man saw that all the troops who came to a halt there.

10:56.668 --> 11:02.875
And when he realized that everyone who came up to Amasa stopped, he dragged him from the road into a field and threw a garment over him.

11:03.235 --> 11:09.322
And after Amasa had been removed from the road, everyone went on with Joab to pursue Shiba, the son of Bakiri.

11:09.622 --> 11:11.605
And all God's people said, yikes.

11:13.066 --> 11:14.708
All right, where do we even start with this?

11:14.808 --> 11:16.530
Let's just go to the beginning.

11:16.834 --> 11:23.104
As soon as David returns to the palace in Jerusalem, he finds the 10 concubines that he had left there to take care of the palace.

11:23.144 --> 11:28.613
But remember, these are the 10 women that his son Absalom had assaulted when he rebelled against David.

11:28.653 --> 11:33.421
And so what David does is he puts them in confinement and they live the rest of their lives as widows.

11:33.481 --> 11:36.786
It's a sad ending for these women who did absolutely nothing wrong.

11:37.090 --> 11:42.376
Then David decides to put together a military plan to go after this traitor named Sheba.

11:42.516 --> 11:48.243
He knows that if he waits too long, Sheba's gonna get away and he can get inside of a fortified city.

11:48.363 --> 11:53.969
And once he's inside the walls of a city, it's gonna be a lot more difficult to get ahold of him and to stop him.

11:53.989 --> 11:56.212
And so he calls for a man named Amasa.

11:56.352 --> 11:58.955
Amasa was Absalom's military commander.

11:59.356 --> 12:01.718
David had promoted him to his military commander.

12:02.199 --> 12:05.042
Problem is, Amasa is a terrible leader.

12:05.314 --> 12:07.657
When David calls for him, homeboy doesn't even show up.

12:08.138 --> 12:09.820
He doesn't even care to come to the party.

12:09.880 --> 12:11.022
He takes way too long.

12:11.422 --> 12:12.724
David doesn't have time to wait.

12:12.844 --> 12:14.467
He needs to go after Shiba now.

12:14.947 --> 12:19.794
So he sends his two most trusted men, Joab and his brother Abishai.

12:20.275 --> 12:22.918
I would love to have a conversation with these guys.

12:22.938 --> 12:29.407
I'd prefer that conversation to happen from a distance, but I would love to at least talk to them and see how all of this went down.

12:29.888 --> 12:31.550
I mean, they're David's most loyal men.

12:31.630 --> 12:34.354
From the very beginning, they've stood by David's side.

12:34.594 --> 12:36.176
But they're also a little bit impulsive.

12:36.616 --> 12:41.662
Joab and Abishai are a little savage in nature in the way they go about things.

12:41.682 --> 12:43.584
And that's clearly seen in this story.

12:44.084 --> 12:45.586
Joab is very deceptive.

12:46.206 --> 12:49.590
And he deceives Amasa in order to take his life.

12:49.970 --> 12:53.374
Remember, Amasa was the one who succeeded him as the military commander.

12:53.694 --> 12:59.641
So Joab likely saw this as an opportunity to take the life of his enemy and to get his job back.

13:00.041 --> 13:00.682
So what does he do?

13:01.223 --> 13:04.466
He tricks Amasa in three different ways, pretending

13:04.578 --> 13:06.380
to be for him and pretending to be friendly.

13:06.440 --> 13:14.369
The first thing is as he goes to greet him, his dagger falls out of its sheath, giving the illusion that he's unarmed.

13:14.389 --> 13:19.535
The second thing is he reaches out and he grabs his beard to kiss him, which might seem really weird in our culture.

13:19.795 --> 13:22.618
But back then, this was just a friendly Jewish welcome.

13:23.119 --> 13:27.744
And the last thing is he grabbed his beard with his right hand, which was his fighting hand.

13:28.064 --> 13:33.010
Amasa would have never expected an attack from a dagger on the ground with the left hand.

13:34.114 --> 13:35.737
and he takes the life of his enemy.

13:36.478 --> 13:47.697
And after that happens, he gathers all of the men together and he forms this alliance that we're gonna go take out Sheba, this traitor, and we're gonna go win back our country for King David.

13:47.977 --> 13:51.303
And all of these men align with Joab and decide to follow him.

13:51.643 --> 13:53.226
Look at what happens next, verse 14.

13:53.607 --> 13:54.809
We'll read through the end of the chapter.

13:55.690 --> 14:00.338
It says, Sheba passed through all the tribes of Israel to Abel Beth Makah

14:00.578 --> 14:04.162
and through the entire region of the bakirai to gather together and follow him.

14:04.983 --> 14:09.209
All the troops with Joab came in besieged Shiba in a bell, Beth Makah.

14:09.669 --> 14:13.774
They built a siege ramp up to the city and it stood against the outer fortifications.

14:14.275 --> 14:19.061
While they were battering the wall to bring it down, a wise woman called from the city.

14:19.441 --> 14:22.765
Listen, listen, tell Joab to come here so I can speak to him.

14:23.326 --> 14:25.789
He went toward her and she asked, are you Joab?

14:26.330 --> 14:27.191
I am, he answered.

14:27.631 --> 14:29.874
She said, listen to what your servant has to say.

14:30.018 --> 14:31.060
I'm listening," he said.

14:31.701 --> 14:36.651
She continued, long ago they used to say, get your answer at a bell and that settled it.

14:37.072 --> 14:39.116
We are the peaceful and faithful in Israel.

14:39.416 --> 14:42.282
You are trying to destroy a city that is a mother in Israel.

14:42.703 --> 14:44.987
Why do you want to swallow up the Lord's inheritance?

14:45.027 --> 14:46.530
And I love what Joab says in verse 20.

14:46.931 --> 14:48.754
Far be it from me, Joab replied.

14:49.175 --> 14:51.941
Far be it from me to swallow up or destroy.

14:52.021 --> 14:52.722
Pause right there.

14:52.930 --> 14:56.455
Didn't he just swallow up and destroy someone a couple of verses earlier?

14:56.775 --> 14:57.376
You love Joab.

14:57.396 --> 14:57.997
He's like, me?

14:58.318 --> 14:58.878
Kill anybody?

14:59.059 --> 14:59.900
No, never.

15:00.300 --> 15:00.861
Verse 21.

15:01.822 --> 15:03.144
That is not the case, he said.

15:03.164 --> 15:10.274
A man named Shiba, the son of Bakiri from the hill country of Ephraim, has lifted up his hand against the king and against David.

15:10.795 --> 15:14.020
Hand over this one man and all withdraw from the city.

15:14.460 --> 15:17.765
The woman said to Joab, his head will be thrown to you from the wall.

15:18.366 --> 15:21.490
Then the woman went to all the people with her wise advice and they cut

15:21.698 --> 15:25.382
off the head of Shiva, the son of Bekiri, and threw it to Joab.

15:25.402 --> 15:32.229
So he sounded the trumpet, and his men dispersed from the city, each returning to his home, and Joab went back to the king in Jerusalem.

15:32.630 --> 15:38.256
Joab was over Israel's entire army, but Naya, the son of Jehoedah, was over the Karathites and the Pelithites.

15:38.676 --> 15:40.539
Adonarayim was in charge of forced labor.

15:40.599 --> 15:42.781
Jehosaphat, the son of Aliyud, was a recorder.

15:43.221 --> 15:48.167
Shiva was secretary, Zaidok, and Abiathar were priests, and Ayra, the gyreite, was David's priest.

15:49.188 --> 15:50.289
Okay, a lot happened here.

15:50.309 --> 15:51.090
Let's break this down.

15:52.162 --> 15:54.945
So David's greatest fear becomes a reality.

15:55.226 --> 15:59.651
Shiba has made his way inside the walls of a fortified city called Abel.

16:00.151 --> 16:04.857
And now that he's saved within these walls, most of the army would have said, oh, we lost our opportunity.

16:05.217 --> 16:06.578
There's no way we're going to get him now.

16:06.619 --> 16:11.064
But if there's anything we know about Joab, he's not going to accept defeat that easily.

16:11.424 --> 16:13.006
So he sets up a siege.

16:13.426 --> 16:16.690
And you're all very familiar with the ancient practice of besiegement.

16:16.930 --> 16:18.312
You've been on a siege recently?

16:18.533 --> 16:18.713
No?

16:18.873 --> 16:19.535
Okay.

16:19.555 --> 16:20.997
So here's what would happen in a siege.

16:21.037 --> 16:22.740
This is probably like what you've seen in movies.

16:22.780 --> 16:28.750
They would establish a perimeter and they would take some large object and start ramming it against the walls or the gates of a city.

16:28.951 --> 16:29.993
Yes, you've seen that in movies.

16:30.453 --> 16:32.918
However, in movies, they always seem to get in.

16:33.338 --> 16:34.060
I don't know why that is.

16:34.120 --> 16:37.385
You ever watched a movie where they ram a tree trunk against the gate and they don't get in?

16:37.806 --> 16:39.229
Every time they seem to break down.

16:39.750 --> 16:42.354
However, in the ancient practice of a siege,

16:42.498 --> 16:45.241
Penetrating the walls of a city was almost impossible.

16:45.541 --> 16:47.043
That usually didn't happen.

16:47.544 --> 16:48.585
So what would the army do?

16:48.625 --> 16:51.128
At that point, it became a waiting game.

16:51.548 --> 16:53.270
They would wait outside the city.

16:53.791 --> 16:56.373
Nothing was allowed in and nothing was allowed out.

16:57.274 --> 17:02.200
Over time, the people would starve to death and they would give the army whatever they wanted.

17:02.701 --> 17:08.026
There's records in ancient history of sieges that lasted five, even 10 years.

17:09.528 --> 17:11.250
And if there's anything we know about Joab,

17:12.130 --> 17:12.631
He can wait.

17:14.133 --> 17:15.194
So he's just sitting outside.

17:16.215 --> 17:19.079
He's like, I'll wait here until you give me what I want.

17:19.099 --> 17:21.081
And there's a wise woman in this city.

17:21.442 --> 17:22.323
And I love what she does.

17:22.423 --> 17:23.504
She's like, you know what?

17:23.685 --> 17:30.493
We could suffer under this years and years and years of devastation or someone can go talk to that guy.

17:31.014 --> 17:31.935
She goes, no one's gonna do it.

17:31.975 --> 17:32.335
I'll do it.

17:32.516 --> 17:33.977
So she goes to the wall, picture this.

17:34.038 --> 17:37.302
She's crying out to the commander of the king's army.

17:37.622 --> 17:39.084
She's like, listen to me, listen to me.

17:39.564 --> 17:40.786
What do you want?

17:40.994 --> 17:43.277
We'll give you whatever you want."

17:43.297 --> 17:47.383
And Joab pretty much answers her and says, listen, ma'am, we don't want any trouble.

17:48.425 --> 17:50.668
We just want the traitor that's in your midst.

17:50.688 --> 17:53.092
There's a guy in there who's rebelled against the king.

17:53.833 --> 17:55.195
That's the only reason we're here.

17:55.836 --> 18:09.336
And so this wise woman goes back to the leaders of the city and she says, listen, guys, we can suffer years of unnecessary pain under siege or we can cut off the head of this traitor and throw it over the wall.

18:10.217 --> 18:10.738
What do you think?

18:12.290 --> 18:16.334
I doubt that was a very long conversation in the leadership council at Abel.

18:17.836 --> 18:24.383
They make a quick decision, they cut off Shiba's head, and they throw it over the wall, and everyone goes about their day.

18:25.424 --> 18:31.751
It's crazy to think that they would rather kill the traitor in their midst than suffer years of unnecessary pain.

18:33.012 --> 18:40.921
There's a great Puritan commentator by the name of John Trapp, and he gives us a spiritual analogy out of this whole situation.

18:40.961 --> 18:41.842
Listen to what he says.

18:42.466 --> 18:48.237
Every man is a city enclosed, and every sin is a traitor that lurks within those walls.

18:48.818 --> 18:54.449
God calleth for Shiba's head, neither hath he any quarrel to us for our person but for our sin.

18:54.509 --> 19:00.782
And if we love the head of our traitor above the life of our soul, we shall justly perish in the vengeance."

19:00.802 --> 19:01.403
What is he saying?

19:01.743 --> 19:05.170
Listen, there is a traitor inside every single one of us.

19:05.346 --> 19:11.114
There is sin inside the walls of your heart, and it is wreaking havoc on your soul.

19:11.154 --> 19:15.801
And God will not just sit by and watch sin ruin your life.

19:16.402 --> 19:21.870
If it feels like you're under siege right now, like there's this pressure on you, your sin is heavy on your heart.

19:22.211 --> 19:24.774
You're sitting under the conviction of the Holy Spirit.

19:25.175 --> 19:27.378
God is doing that because He loves you.

19:27.618 --> 19:29.800
God is pursuing you in His grace.

19:30.161 --> 19:34.525
He has set up a perimeter around your life and says, I'm not here to destroy you.

19:34.545 --> 19:35.907
I just want the traitor.

19:35.967 --> 19:39.451
I just want the traitor inside your walls.

19:40.172 --> 19:42.074
So listen, you have a choice to make.

19:42.454 --> 19:47.760
You can suffer through years of unnecessary pain or you can cut off the traitor's head and throw it over the wall.

19:48.160 --> 19:49.021
The choice is yours.

19:50.443 --> 19:51.304
You have a decision.

19:52.545 --> 19:53.586
You might say, well, Jaden,

19:54.082 --> 19:55.103
Cut off the traitor's head.

19:55.123 --> 19:56.806
I mean, that's a radical concept.

19:56.826 --> 19:58.688
That's like Old Testament stuff, right?

19:59.830 --> 20:03.676
No, this same concept is repeated over and over again in the New Testament, too.

20:03.996 --> 20:05.558
And it uses almost the same language.

20:05.598 --> 20:06.099
Listen to this.

20:06.179 --> 20:07.761
This is Paul in Romans 8, 13.

20:08.502 --> 20:11.767
For if you live according to the flesh, you will die.

20:11.827 --> 20:13.509
But if by the spirit, you what?

20:14.170 --> 20:17.355
Put to death the misdeeds of the body, you will live.

20:17.956 --> 20:22.482
Paul seems to suggest this is a matter of life and death, whether you kill the traitor or not.

20:22.658 --> 20:25.682
He says it this way, Colossians 3.5, put to what?

20:25.722 --> 20:29.607
Death, therefore, whatever belongs to your earthly nature.

20:30.027 --> 20:34.994
Sexual immorality, impurity, lust, evil desires, and greed, which is idolatry.

20:35.935 --> 20:47.429
Listen, I don't know what traitor is inside the walls of your life, but whatever form it takes, whether it's sexual immorality, impurity, lust, evil desires, greed, which is idolatry, it's time that the traitor dies.

20:48.490 --> 20:51.314
It's time that its head is cut off and thrown over the wall.

20:51.586 --> 20:57.577
And when you do that, I promise you will experience the joy and the freedom of walking and obedience to Christ.

20:57.877 --> 21:09.559
But the longer you live with it, the longer you let that traitor live, the more disappointed you will become, and the more miserable your life will be.

21:10.961 --> 21:12.063
It's time the traitor dies.

21:12.905 --> 21:15.730
Experience the joy and the freedom of walking with Christ.

21:16.098 --> 21:19.262
Now look at chapter 21, we're gonna read the first 14 verses together.

21:19.642 --> 21:22.505
I want you to see the whole picture of this story as it unfolds.

21:22.565 --> 21:28.212
The army has returned back to Jerusalem, and now there's even more devastation in David's life.

21:28.332 --> 21:29.613
Look at verse one of chapter 21.

21:30.855 --> 21:35.020
During the reign of David, there was a famine for three successive years.

21:35.580 --> 21:37.482
So David sought the face of the Lord.

21:37.903 --> 21:41.547
And the Lord said, it is on account of Saul in his blood-stained house.

21:42.028 --> 21:44.210
It's because he put the Gibeonites to death.

21:44.642 --> 21:46.605
The king summoned the Gibeonites and spoke to them.

21:46.845 --> 21:56.761
Now the Gibeonites were not part of Israel, but were survivors of the Amorites, for the Israelites had sworn to spare them, but Saul and his zeal for Israel and Judah had tried to annihilate them.

21:57.201 --> 21:59.625
So David asked the Gibeonites, what shall I do for you?

22:00.046 --> 22:01.107
How shall I make what?

22:01.908 --> 22:04.793
Atonement so that you will bless the Lord's inheritance.

22:04.813 --> 22:13.426
Verse four, the Gibeonites answered him, we have no right to demand silver or gold from Saul or his family, nor do we have the right to put anyone to death in Israel.

22:13.698 --> 22:15.500
So what do you want me to do for you, David asked?

22:15.861 --> 22:16.602
They answered the king.

22:17.283 --> 22:31.702
As for the man who destroyed us and plotted against us so that we have been decimated and have no place anywhere in Israel, let seven of his male descendants be given to us to be killed, and there's bodies exposed before the Lord at Gibia of Saul, the Lord's chosen one.

22:32.103 --> 22:34.546
So the king said, I will give them to you.

22:34.978 --> 22:41.285
The king spared Mephibosheth, son of Jonathan, the son of Saul, because of the oath before the Lord between David and Jonathan, the son of Saul.

22:41.685 --> 22:58.804
But the king took Armani and Mephibosheth, the two sons of Aya's daughter, Rispa, whom she had born to Saul, together with the five sons of Saul's daughter, Marab, who she had born to Adriel, the son of Barzillai, the Mahalithite, and he handed them over to the Gimini to kill them and expose their bodies on a hill before the Lord.

22:59.364 --> 23:01.106
All seven of them fell together,

23:01.474 --> 23:06.662
and they were put to death during the first days of the harvest, just as the barley harvest was beginning, verse 10.

23:07.603 --> 23:12.150
Rispa, daughter of Aya, took sackcloth and spread it out for herself on a rock.

23:12.610 --> 23:19.961
From the beginning of the harvest till the rain poured down from the heavens on the body, she did not let the birds touch them by day, or the wild animals by night.

23:20.342 --> 23:28.914
And when David was told what Aya's daughter, Rispa, Saul's concubine had done, he went and took the bones of Saul and his son, Jonathan, from the citizens of J. Beshgiliad.

23:29.090 --> 23:35.676
They had stolen their bodies from the public square at Beth Sean, where the Philistines had hung them after they struck Saul down on Gilboa.

23:36.157 --> 23:41.642
David brought the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan from there, and the bones of those who had been killed and exposed were gathered up.

23:42.183 --> 23:49.330
They buried the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan in the tomb of Saul's father, Kish, at Zayla and Benjamin, and did everything the king commanded.

23:49.830 --> 23:51.692
After that, God answered what?

23:52.513 --> 23:54.715
Prayer and behalf of the land.

23:56.056 --> 23:57.938
So chapter 21 begins,

23:58.530 --> 24:01.573
with a three-year-long famine in the land.

24:02.334 --> 24:06.498
Now in those days, a famine was almost always due to a drought.

24:06.878 --> 24:09.221
They didn't have irrigation systems back then.

24:09.261 --> 24:11.823
So if it didn't rain, you couldn't grow crops.

24:11.863 --> 24:14.025
If you couldn't grow crops, you couldn't eat food.

24:15.006 --> 24:17.429
And so the people are beginning to be hungry.

24:18.129 --> 24:19.871
They're experiencing great loss.

24:20.872 --> 24:22.294
And David does the right thing.

24:22.334 --> 24:24.496
He sought the face of the Lord.

24:25.437 --> 24:26.738
He goes to the Lord,

24:27.074 --> 24:29.097
and he prays, God, why is this happening to us?

24:29.799 --> 24:32.183
And the Lord gives him a very clear answer in verse one.

24:32.343 --> 24:37.452
It is on account of Saul and his blood-stained house because he put the Gibeonites to death.

24:37.933 --> 24:43.442
Now, in order to understand this, we need to rewind 350 years all the way to the book of Joshua.

24:43.554 --> 24:48.082
When Joshua was leading God's people into the Promised Land, he was taking ground.

24:48.142 --> 24:54.173
He was fighting all of the Canaanite nations that were in the Promised Land so that Israel could inhabit them.

24:54.214 --> 25:00.986
God told Joshua, don't make a treaty with any of these nations that live right here in the Promised Land because you're going to have to defeat them.

25:01.427 --> 25:04.112
However, the Gibeonites bamboozled Joshua.

25:04.372 --> 25:05.394
They showed up

25:05.506 --> 25:07.808
As if they were coming from a faraway land.

25:07.848 --> 25:08.990
Their clothes were torn.

25:09.070 --> 25:10.731
They had dirt on their sandals.

25:10.791 --> 25:12.833
They put no water in their cantines.

25:13.254 --> 25:16.217
And they showed up, we've come from a faraway land to make a treaty with you.

25:16.597 --> 25:20.561
And Joshua agreed, made a treaty with them, that Israel would not defeat them.

25:20.982 --> 25:22.884
However, they weren't from faraway.

25:23.324 --> 25:25.226
They were from right down the block.

25:25.246 --> 25:27.388
But God told Joshua, you gave them your word.

25:27.508 --> 25:29.430
God cares about what we give our word.

25:29.470 --> 25:30.251
We have to honor it.

25:30.691 --> 25:33.234
Joshua made a promise in a treaty that he would not attack them.

25:33.506 --> 25:36.950
Fast forward 350 years later to King Saul.

25:37.590 --> 25:41.094
King Saul, we know, is a little bit impulsive and prideful in his leadership.

25:41.455 --> 25:47.301
And it says, out of his zeal for Israel and Judah, he attacked the Gibeonites and put them to death.

25:48.162 --> 25:55.010
He went against a treaty that Israel had made years earlier and sinned against the Lord by going against Israel's promise.

25:55.891 --> 26:00.576
And now God says, this famine in the land is because of what Saul did.

26:01.537 --> 26:02.578
So what does David do?

26:03.042 --> 26:04.324
He seeks to make it right.

26:04.925 --> 26:08.551
It says that he seeks to make atonement on behalf of the people.

26:08.851 --> 26:13.338
So he calls the Gibeonites in, he says, what do we need to do to settle this debt?

26:13.859 --> 26:14.860
How do we make this right?

26:15.301 --> 26:16.062
And what's their answer?

26:16.122 --> 26:22.212
They want seven descendants, seven sons of Saul to be killed.

26:23.534 --> 26:23.855
Anything.

26:24.636 --> 26:26.919
There's no way David's gonna agree to that, right?

26:28.061 --> 26:31.186
But he agrees to it a little more quickly than we would like him to.

26:31.842 --> 26:34.266
He simply just says, yes, and makes it happen.

26:34.706 --> 26:38.472
Now, we don't know exactly why David agreed so quickly, but we know this.

26:38.532 --> 26:40.235
He did it because he cared about his people.

26:41.016 --> 26:48.427
He had an opportunity to write a wrong from many, many years earlier, and he decides to go forward with it.

26:48.747 --> 26:54.135
And on a larger scale, you could say this, David understood that sin had to be atoned for.

26:54.175 --> 26:57.921
There is a price that must be paid for sin.

26:57.981 --> 26:58.642
Did you know that?

26:58.946 --> 27:02.712
Even in the New Testament, Romans 6, it says, the wages of sin is what?

27:03.613 --> 27:03.913
Death.

27:04.975 --> 27:12.286
Sin requires payment, someone laying down their life so that the sin can be forgiven.

27:13.067 --> 27:17.113
And after these lives are laid down, their bodies are sacrificed.

27:17.493 --> 27:19.677
God answers prayer on behalf of the land.

27:20.898 --> 27:26.126
One of the cool things about this story is it isn't just true history of something that happened 3,000 years ago.

27:26.867 --> 27:28.690
This story is pointing ahead

27:28.994 --> 27:31.057
to the message of the gospel of Jesus Christ.

27:31.497 --> 27:32.739
Think about some of these details.

27:34.061 --> 27:38.447
Men laid down their lives as atonement for sins that they did not commit.

27:39.488 --> 27:44.896
Kind of like Jesus Christ, who laid down his life as an atoning sacrifice for sins that he did not commit.

27:45.597 --> 27:49.502
At the moment of death, the payment is accepted and God's wrath is satisfied.

27:49.582 --> 27:55.631
When Jesus said it is finished, the payment was accepted and God's wrath was satisfied fully in Christ.

27:56.252 --> 27:58.034
What happened after the men died?

27:58.402 --> 28:02.467
After their bodies were exposed, there was an outward symbol in the sky.

28:02.747 --> 28:08.294
The rain that came down from the heavens was an outward sign that the payment was received.

28:08.514 --> 28:12.239
And when Jesus died on the cross, there was an outward symbol in the sky.

28:12.319 --> 28:13.761
The sky turned black.

28:14.121 --> 28:18.547
Everything went dark as a symbol that the payment had been received in the eyes of God.

28:19.027 --> 28:21.751
The bodies of these men are displayed on a what?

28:22.432 --> 28:24.354
A hill for everyone to see.

28:24.835 --> 28:27.698
Jesus Christ was sacrificed on a cross.

28:27.810 --> 28:29.752
crucified and placed on a what?

28:30.373 --> 28:32.196
A hill for everyone to see.

28:32.696 --> 28:48.276
And finally, this woman, Rispa, shows up to care for the bodies of the men who lay down their lives, kind of like the women showed up at the tomb three days later to care for the body of Jesus, only to find that the body of Jesus wasn't there because he was resurrected in power and seated at the right hand of God.

28:49.057 --> 28:56.146
Listen, this story, even from 3,000 years ago, is pointing us to the message of the gospel of Jesus Christ.

28:56.354 --> 28:59.959
These Old Testament stories are amazing, and they teach us so many things.

29:00.059 --> 29:04.065
But so often, if you look closely, they're pointing us to what Jesus would do.

29:04.726 --> 29:06.108
We're going to close in verse 15.

29:06.148 --> 29:07.310
We'll read to the end of the chapter.

29:07.590 --> 29:07.971
It says this.

29:09.993 --> 29:17.284
Once again, there was a battle between the Philistines and Israel, and David went down with his men to fight against the Philistines, and he became what?

29:18.145 --> 29:18.866
Exhausted.

29:19.554 --> 29:28.164
Anishbi Benab, one of the descendants of Raffa, whose bronze spearhead weighed 300 shekels and who was armed with a new sword, said he would kill David.

29:28.645 --> 29:31.468
But Abishai the son of Zoriah came to David's rescue.

29:31.849 --> 29:34.072
He struck the Philistine down and killed him.

29:34.532 --> 29:41.821
Then David's men swore to him, saying, never again will you go out to battle with us, so that the lamp of Israel will not be extinguished.

29:41.841 --> 29:42.422
Verse 18.

29:43.243 --> 29:46.647
In the course of time, there was another battle with the Philistines at Gabb.

29:46.987 --> 29:49.330
At that time, Sebecchai, the Hushatite,

29:49.506 --> 29:51.669
killed Saf, one of the descendants of Raffa.

29:52.269 --> 29:59.158
In another battle with the Philistines at Gabb, Elinah of Jair, the Bethlehemite, killed the brother of Goliath the Gittai.

29:59.198 --> 29:59.639
Remember him?

30:00.079 --> 30:02.422
Who had a spear with a shaft like a weaver's rod.

30:02.903 --> 30:11.694
In still another battle, which took place at Gath, there was a huge man with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot, 24 in all.

30:11.814 --> 30:13.636
In all God's people said, gross.

30:14.758 --> 30:16.780
And he was also a descendant from Raffa.

30:17.040 --> 30:18.322
Last verse, verse 21.

30:18.914 --> 30:23.219
When he taunted Israel, Jonathan, the son of Shami'i, David's brother, killed him.

30:23.579 --> 30:28.725
And these four were descendants of Raffa and Gath, and they fell at the hands of David and his men.

30:29.285 --> 30:30.847
What a way to end the chapter, huh?

30:31.608 --> 30:35.532
David's men just kicking butt and taking names out here.

30:35.552 --> 30:41.619
David goes out to fight alongside his men, which is an important statement, because remember, at this point, how old is David?

30:42.800 --> 30:43.761
70 years old.

30:44.662 --> 30:47.986
He could probably still swing a sword, but I'm willing to bet not like he used to.

30:48.738 --> 30:51.041
And he becomes exhausted on the battlefield.

30:51.061 --> 30:55.107
So David's men say, listen, we don't want you to go out and fight with us anymore.

30:55.808 --> 30:58.332
We don't want the lamp of Israel to be extinguished.

30:59.334 --> 31:01.076
Think about how hard that must have been for David.

31:01.677 --> 31:03.079
He's the one who killed Goliath.

31:03.320 --> 31:03.780
Are you kidding?

31:04.481 --> 31:08.768
It's like I'm the one who fought all these great battles for Israel, but David understood something.

31:09.088 --> 31:12.994
His legacy did not lie in the giant that he killed for his generation.

31:13.034 --> 31:18.482
His legacy was in the men that he raised up to kill giants for future generations of Israel.

31:18.882 --> 31:26.293
There were men that were being trained as warriors in the kingdom of God to face giants in their day.

31:27.134 --> 31:30.519
I love how verse 17, David's men call him the lamp of Israel.

31:30.599 --> 31:35.867
They call him that because he lit the way for future warriors to walk down in future generations.

31:36.949 --> 31:44.941
And because of David's investment, because he didn't let his legacy just die with him, he raised up other young men as warriors.

31:45.041 --> 31:48.466
And because of that investment, the kingdom of Israel is in good hands.

31:48.802 --> 31:50.865
I love what G. Campbell Morgan had to say about this.

31:50.885 --> 32:04.582
He said, let those who after long service find themselves waning in strength be content to abide with the people of God still shining for them as a lamp and thus enabling them to carry on the same divine enterprises.

32:05.023 --> 32:10.890
Such action in the last days of life is also great and high service.

32:10.910 --> 32:16.137
God is called every single one of us to pass on a legacy to the next generation.

32:16.157 --> 32:16.978
Because guess what?

32:17.730 --> 32:20.213
There's still giants out there that we're fighting today, aren't there?

32:21.335 --> 32:22.837
There are still battles to be won.

32:23.538 --> 32:26.922
There are still victories to claim in the name of our God.

32:27.884 --> 32:34.913
But because of the investment of this generation into the next one, I believe that the kingdom of God is in good hands.

32:34.933 --> 32:38.999
There's a generation rising up right now of young people who love Jesus.

32:39.059 --> 32:39.600
Did you know that?

32:40.140 --> 32:43.064
God's doing something with the young people of our church and our city.

32:43.104 --> 32:44.306
It's amazing.

32:47.042 --> 32:51.286
I didn't have a conversation with one of these teenagers or young adults and say, tell me your story.

32:52.027 --> 32:53.168
What's God doing in your life?

32:54.029 --> 32:59.254
I'm evidence of the fact that God is raising up a generation that loves Christ.

32:59.714 --> 33:07.221
If I were to tell you my story, I would tell you the only reason I'm standing here today is because of the faithfulness and grace of God.

33:07.802 --> 33:16.690
But I'll also say it's because men invested in my life, there were hardly men who poured into me, who saw something in me that I didn't even see in myself.

33:17.122 --> 33:19.925
If there were a book written about this, this is what it would sound like.

33:20.686 --> 33:26.073
There was a kid named Javan who was a knucklehead and a punk who showed up to CCA in 2005.

33:27.575 --> 33:29.717
He was prideful and arrogant.

33:30.418 --> 33:33.522
He was passionate, but that passion was completely misguided.

33:34.263 --> 33:35.925
And people saw, oh, amen to that?

33:35.965 --> 33:36.366
All right, cool.

33:37.527 --> 33:37.687
Yeah.

33:38.648 --> 33:39.029
Thank you.

33:39.530 --> 33:43.154
Appreciate the reminder.

33:44.802 --> 33:47.966
And someone saw something in that kid that he didn't see in himself.

33:48.907 --> 33:53.873
And someone invested in him, and poured into him, and raised him up.

33:55.475 --> 33:57.498
And my story would never be the same without that.

33:59.360 --> 34:02.764
I've never seen a church invest in the next generation like this one.

34:03.745 --> 34:09.613
I've never seen a church take the mission of God as seriously as this one.

34:09.633 --> 34:10.614
So what does that mean for you?

34:10.674 --> 34:14.098
You have a spiritual responsibility.

34:14.818 --> 34:18.223
to pass on the legacy of a warrior to the next generation.

34:18.904 --> 34:22.448
And I'll tell you this, you know God's gonna do it with or without you.

34:23.730 --> 34:24.211
Did you know that?

34:24.852 --> 34:29.638
This generation is gonna be raised up as warriors for Christ with or without you.

34:30.860 --> 34:34.285
Jesus will build his church and the gates of hell will not prevail against it.

34:34.385 --> 34:39.251
I promise you, the view is so much better from the field than it is from the sideline.

34:39.272 --> 34:44.018
Maybe there's some of you today, God is calling you to step foot into the game to make a difference.

34:44.386 --> 34:47.010
to pass on a legacy of faith to the next generation.

34:48.032 --> 34:49.534
I'm so glad that David did that.

34:51.016 --> 34:52.899
And he had every reason not to, didn't he?

34:53.540 --> 34:56.144
Think about everything that David's gone through in the last couple of chapters.

34:56.485 --> 35:03.335
Two rebellions, two civil wars, the death of his son, tragedy after tragedy after tragedy.

35:03.416 --> 35:06.560
David had every reason to throw in the towel and just say, this is hopeless.

35:06.881 --> 35:08.303
But he understood something about God.

35:08.383 --> 35:12.690
The Lord often does his best work in the most hopeful looking situations.

35:12.962 --> 35:16.446
Even in the midst of tragedy, God can bring revival.

35:16.987 --> 35:19.711
And that happened right here in our own backyard just last year.

35:20.391 --> 35:29.763
I want you to hear the story of the Matthew family and see how God can take something that causes such deep pain, God can take tragedy and turn it into revival.

35:29.964 --> 35:30.524
Take a look at this.

35:36.372 --> 35:38.395
I've been married to Jason for 20 years.

35:38.795 --> 35:41.138
We were both introduced by our uncles

35:41.282 --> 35:43.705
It was like God putting the chess pieces together.

35:43.725 --> 35:49.172
I started exchanging emails, I talked on the phone with each other, and 11 months later we were married.

35:49.632 --> 35:54.418
We both loved kids, and so we always knew that we wanted a big family.

35:54.959 --> 35:57.702
Before we knew it, we all had all of our four kids.

35:57.802 --> 35:59.044
Los Angeles is the oldest.

35:59.645 --> 36:00.966
She was 15.

36:01.026 --> 36:03.089
Caris is 14.

36:03.850 --> 36:06.052
Rayma is 11, and Luke is nine.

36:06.093 --> 36:08.055
So we have three girls and one boy.

36:08.355 --> 36:10.578
God has blessed us with four beautiful children.

36:15.138 --> 36:21.588
Sayla was my princess, my angel, my firstborn, my right hand.

36:22.810 --> 36:23.912
She loved being a big sister.

36:25.033 --> 36:26.075
She loved her family.

36:26.576 --> 36:27.858
She loved her friends even more.

36:28.559 --> 36:30.622
And she was good at everything she did.

36:30.642 --> 36:38.354
You know, sometimes, you know, we would get busy in the evenings and she would, you know, do devotions with aggressive lanes.

36:38.818 --> 36:44.766
read the Bible with them and worship with them and just pray and she would take care of them and without us even asking.

36:44.887 --> 36:46.849
So she was the first child.

36:46.889 --> 36:53.960
You wanted her to be perfect and I think that's kind of what motivated her to have that, you know, perfection attitude.

36:54.260 --> 36:57.965
But later on you saw her that it just grew from, hey, I want to be perfect.

36:58.146 --> 36:59.748
I want to serve God.

36:59.768 --> 37:01.751
I want to have that spirit of excellence.

37:01.771 --> 37:04.114
And so that was beautiful to see.

37:06.818 --> 37:13.227
She dreamed about being part of the dance team at CCA, and she got to live that out.

37:13.247 --> 37:21.778
That was her favorite place.

37:21.798 --> 37:23.020
I love seeing her up there.

37:25.023 --> 37:28.908
She has a very special glow.

37:28.928 --> 37:30.610
I love seeing her live out her dream.

37:34.498 --> 37:39.004
She called me on a Wednesday saying she was going to stay afterwards at school.

37:39.184 --> 37:43.090
And as I pulled into the parking lot, normally I would have just got on my phone or listened to the radio.

37:43.110 --> 37:50.760
But because we're in the middle of the fast, I just figured I would get out of the car and just start walking around the church building and the school and just start praying.

37:51.401 --> 37:56.808
As I got behind the youth building, I felt an option to pray for revival, revival among the youth.

37:56.988 --> 38:04.338
And so I didn't think anything about just start praying for revival and made it back to the car and Sailor met me at the car.

38:04.610 --> 38:09.817
That was everyone coming.

38:09.837 --> 38:12.441
So the next day, I left work at around five o'clock.

38:12.461 --> 38:15.566
I got a phone call from a sailor's phone, actually.

38:15.866 --> 38:16.928
And so I thought it was sailor.

38:16.948 --> 38:19.311
I picked up the phone and it was one of her teachers.

38:19.792 --> 38:21.774
And she's like, my name's Miss Fox.

38:21.794 --> 38:24.879
I'm in the ambulance with her daughter.

38:24.919 --> 38:29.906
She's had a allergic reaction backstage and we're on our way to the hospital.

38:36.898 --> 38:45.988
They landed on my truck.

38:46.008 --> 38:53.636
When I went back into the ER, I saw at least a dozen medical professionals working on Salem.

38:53.996 --> 38:55.678
That's when I realized how serious she was.

38:58.741 --> 39:03.026
Maybe about 15 minutes later, Smith will

39:03.266 --> 39:08.011
came walking in and I just looked around the eyes and said, now's not the time to panic.

39:08.191 --> 39:11.455
This is the time to break.

39:11.475 --> 39:12.636
And we held each other's hand.

39:14.518 --> 39:17.421
And from that minute, we started praying.

39:18.643 --> 39:29.034
But as we were waiting, even after we got into the ICU floor and we couldn't go in while they were still stabilizing her, we could see through the glass door.

39:30.215 --> 39:32.658
On the other side, the CCA community

39:33.282 --> 39:34.203
and the church community.

39:34.804 --> 39:43.314
There's probably about 50, 60 people standing outside and a lot of her friends came to the hospital and came into the room and prayed for Salem.

39:43.334 --> 39:47.760
A lot of times I was there first time praying in front of anybody else.

39:47.780 --> 39:54.328
And I remember some of the ladies that came and anointed her with oil and prayed.

39:54.648 --> 39:59.314
And I was learning how to pray as I was watching these ladies pray powerful prayers.

40:00.450 --> 40:06.600
A few days later, Denise Taylor had put out an announcement that she needs our prayers.

40:06.941 --> 40:11.328
And then she organized on the following Tuesday, the prayer by the flagpole.

40:12.690 --> 40:19.481
We thought, all these prayers must mean something, Lord, that you have a plan to resurrect her.

40:20.382 --> 40:25.170
And then she's gonna have such a big testimony to tell others.

40:30.338 --> 40:37.386
So slowly it started setting in that we weren't going to see the resurrection that we had prayed for.

40:37.406 --> 40:43.494
And so they had taken their time doing rounds that morning just to give us more time with Salah, but around noon they came in the room.

40:43.574 --> 40:53.085
They took her off the ventilator and it's really hard to explain on one hand as a father.

40:53.826 --> 40:57.490
You're so disappointed to experience that loss.

40:58.434 --> 41:04.624
But after a week of being in the hospital, we knew that we knew that God's presence was with us.

41:05.185 --> 41:11.795
And even though it didn't make sense with our minds, we almost felt like God's arms were wrapped around us at that time.

41:12.556 --> 41:13.978
But I think he had the best plan.

41:16.242 --> 41:17.664
He knows what is needed.

41:19.447 --> 41:26.578
And he didn't let any of those prayers be wasted, even though we didn't see Salah.

41:27.458 --> 41:29.080
being raised here on Earth.

41:30.001 --> 41:32.385
She was raised into new life in heaven.

41:33.226 --> 41:36.710
She got to be in her favorite place with her Heavenly Father.

41:37.612 --> 41:40.135
We can completely heal and completely heal.

41:40.976 --> 41:44.161
And we've imagined as a family that she is dancing away.

41:45.562 --> 41:50.109
Weeks after, we realized a lot of the kids had the same questions as her friends.

41:51.130 --> 41:54.194
And I was asked by Pastor Bill at the school.

41:54.722 --> 41:57.946
I wanted to lead some chapels with him and answer some of the kids' questions.

41:57.986 --> 42:02.132
I realized from the beginning that we had to walk this walk with a lot of our friends.

42:02.392 --> 42:11.805
It kind of forced me to open up and to talk about my struggles and my disappointment laying them at God's feet, even when our emotions don't line up with our expectations.

42:12.426 --> 42:16.451
God's word is still His word, and it's something that we could stand on.

42:17.092 --> 42:21.458
I believe 20 kids came forward and gave their lives to Christ.

42:21.762 --> 42:22.984
on the day of her memorial.

42:23.204 --> 42:26.268
So the kids had this urgency in their heart.

42:26.408 --> 42:28.991
They felt that they wanted to be baptized right away.

42:30.193 --> 42:34.358
When Sela went to be with the Lord, we realized that she had left everything behind.

42:34.398 --> 42:37.583
There wasn't even one thing that she took with her.

42:37.983 --> 42:41.408
He allowed her life to make such a change.

42:41.788 --> 42:49.458
A small little seed that went into the ground and he allowed her to become this big tree that's giving life to others.

42:51.330 --> 42:57.641
I remember sitting on the stage during that last chapel and remembering that I prayed for a revival.

42:59.504 --> 43:05.374
It was totally different than what I had pictured being, but I knew that God was answering that prayer.

43:05.394 --> 43:14.450
It was a verse in Acts 13 where we were talking about David and how he served the purposes of God, fulfilled the purposes of God.

43:14.818 --> 43:19.084
and slept, and I felt like God was telling me that I could insert a sailor's name in there.

43:19.104 --> 43:21.588
She fulfilled the purposes of God in her generation.

43:22.750 --> 43:28.899
I think that's what she would tell each and every one of us, you know, are we, whether we're going to live to 15 or 50 or 100?

43:28.919 --> 43:36.050
Are we fulfilling the purposes of God in our generation?

43:47.650 --> 43:50.955
You know, something that Jason said at the end of that video that stood out to me.

43:52.177 --> 44:01.873
He said, whether we live to be 15, 50, or 100, are we fulfilling the purposes of God in our generation?

44:01.893 --> 44:07.442
You know, Sala left a legacy of faith, a legacy of joy that will live on forever.

44:09.346 --> 44:11.169
So we'll end the same way that we began.

44:12.711 --> 44:14.514
What kind of legacy do you want to leave?

44:16.770 --> 44:21.396
You might be here today asking questions, trying to figure out your purpose in life.

44:22.958 --> 44:26.102
You might have every reason right now to throw in the towel and give up.

44:27.904 --> 44:28.445
Don't give up.

44:29.727 --> 44:31.469
Don't quit.

44:31.489 --> 44:36.556
Because even in the midst of the tragedies of our world today, the kingdom of God is still on the move.

44:37.056 --> 44:38.518
Let's pray.

44:38.538 --> 44:44.466
God Almighty Jesus Christ, our Savior and our King, we thank you for your goodness and your grace to us.

44:44.738 --> 44:45.923
Thank you for the cross.

44:46.023 --> 44:49.155
Thank you for the resurrection that gives us life and victory.

44:49.175 --> 44:51.243
Oh, death, where is your sting?

44:51.444 --> 44:53.111
Oh, hell, where is your victory?

44:53.131 --> 44:56.082
It is gone because of what Jesus has done.

44:56.162 --> 45:01.410
So we declare the praises of him who called us out of darkness and into his marvelous light.

45:01.470 --> 45:08.480
We thank you for the resurrection power that lives within us, the same power that rose Jesus from the dead.

45:08.881 --> 45:14.930
So Lord, give us the endurance, help us to fix our eyes on you, the author and finisher of our faith.

45:14.978 --> 45:21.071
Help us to carry the gospel wherever we go to our workplaces, our homes, our neighborhoods, our schools.

45:21.552 --> 45:28.246
Jesus light us on fire with the passion of the gospel, that we will proclaim your name, that many would come to know you.

45:28.547 --> 45:30.130
Lord, we pray, do it again.

45:30.178 --> 45:37.695
The revivals that we've seen of old, the revivals in this country, and around the world, God, do it again, do it again, do it again.

45:38.116 --> 45:42.486
Let us see revival with our own eyes, and we will give you all the praise and all the glory.

45:42.907 --> 45:44.230
In Jesus' name we pray.

45:44.250 --> 45:44.811
And everyone said?

45:45.934 --> 45:47.698
Amen, amen, amen.

45:49.282 --> 45:50.865
Thanks for listening to today's message.

45:51.405 --> 45:55.652
You know, here at Calvary, we believe a relationship with Jesus changes everything.

45:55.672 --> 46:02.884
And if you've decided to follow Jesus, we'd love for you to text the word belief to 31352, so you can find out what it means to follow Christ.

46:03.686 --> 46:08.914
And to learn more about Calvary and all of our campuses, you're free to visit calvaryftl.org.

